Commissioner at Shanghai, who is on the trip with us, and I are stay-
ing at the airport over night. We hope to get away early tomorrow mor
ning, fly to Chengtu 175 miles by air ( two weeks by sedan chair) and
return here the same day. We would like to spend more time there but
I should be back in Shanghai as soon as possible and by returning
tomorrow I can catch the regular plane from Chungking to Hankow on
Friday and then connect with the regular plane out of Hankow for
Shanghai
on Saturday.
We have had a marvelous trip so far. Left Shanghai Friday morn-
ing and flew above great white fleecy clouds all the way to Hankow.
The sun was shining brightly on the clouds and through the holes in
the clouds we could look down another two or three thousand feet to
the rice fields below. At Hankow we were held up by bad weather all
day Saturday which we spent
in the Hankow Country Club watching a
base ball game taking a swim and in the evening going to a picture
show (Washington Masquerade) and if you please playing 18 holes of
minature golf. The following morning, Sunday, we left Hankow and flew
westward along the Yangstze to Ichang where the gorges begin. We then
followed the cavern like Yangstze for more than a hundred miles, the
same route was taken by Father and Mother and Ralph in 1929 but it ro
quired almost a week for them against an hour for us. I took along a
borrowed camera and got some good movies of the gorges, that is I took
some great shots if they turn out O.K. Plan to have the films devel-
oped and send them to Debby with the request that she forward them to
Ralph if he is not at the Lake. We had
the good fortune to catch up
with the regular plane of CNAC while in the gorges and I got some good
pictures of that ship in the air. It was the first time that two air-
planes ever went through the gorges together and the natives were so
impressed that they forgot to pull their boats up stream while we were
flying over head, but instead just stared up at us.
